00:15:12.799 --> 00:15:19.660
At the Boys and Girls Clubs we serve about
1,100 kids every single day about 1,800 kids

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:25.439
come at least 50 times or more a year, basically
around once a week across nine different locations

00:15:25.439 --> 00:15:31.379
all in East Palo Alto, Eastern Menlo Park
and unincorporated part of Redwood City.

00:15:31.379 --> 00:15:39.319
So we have about 180 employees who work with
us 45 full time and about 135 or so part time.

00:15:39.319 --> 00:15:43.470
The employees are really, the staff is really
where the magic happens because what we do

00:15:43.470 --> 00:15:47.769
with the youth, folks like Nancy, it's not
about a new program, it's not about a new

00:15:47.769 --> 00:15:50.470
technology, it's about relationships.

00:15:50.470 --> 00:15:54.499
And the only way you can really help these
young people achieve their potential is by

00:15:54.499 --> 00:15:57.240
connecting with them and they have to trust
you.

00:15:57.240 --> 00:16:00.109
And it's only through a meaningful relationship
that that can happen.

00:16:00.109 --> 00:16:03.790
So the most important thing for us at the
Boys and Girls Clubs is having the right staff

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:10.089
and I'm gonna introduce the woman Miss Cherie
Kabba who runs our computer club house in

00:16:10.089 --> 00:16:11.199
East Palo Alto.

00:16:11.199 --> 00:16:17.109
She's absolutely one of our star staff because
she's an amazing technologist, she could be

00:16:17.109 --> 00:16:20.910
working here at Google if she wanted to, she
knows everything about technology there is

00:16:20.910 --> 00:16:27.940
to know but even more importantly she's a
kid magnet and you'll know why.

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:32.420
And she gets the kids and they get her and
she's able to use the technology but then

00:16:32.420 --> 00:16:37.381
more importantly has a relationship to influence
the kids in East Palo Alto community, to stay

00:16:37.381 --> 00:16:39.990
in school, to make the right choices.

00:16:39.990 --> 00:16:44.839
So I'd like to ask Miss Chillin to come share
her perspective of why she's a Boys and Girls

00:16:44.839 --> 00:16:46.639
Club staff person.

00:16:46.639 --> 00:16:47.839
[Applause]

00:16:47.839 --> 00:16:51.689
&gt;&gt;Cherie Kabba: Thank you very much.

00:16:51.689 --> 00:16:53.249
I am Cherie Kabba.

00:16:53.249 --> 00:16:56.410
The kids call me Miss Chillin', my stage name
is Chillin the conscious poet.

00:16:56.410 --> 00:17:03.000
I'm a retired poet, been on stage 25 years
and I like to think that I work for one of

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.220
the most amazing nonprofit organizations in
the country.

00:17:06.220 --> 00:17:10.949
And the reason why I say that is not cause
of the awesome staff but it's because of the

00:17:10.949 --> 00:17:11.949
kids.

00:17:11.949 --> 00:17:14.569
This is the fourth state that I've lived in,
California.

00:17:14.569 --> 00:17:19.620
The community that I work in, East Palo Alto,
reflects the community that I come from in

00:17:19.620 --> 00:17:24.189
inner city Chicago and I'm just really blessed
to have the opportunity to share the space

00:17:24.189 --> 00:17:25.189
with them.

00:17:25.189 --> 00:17:29.270
I believe nothing happens by mistake and so
I'm there for a reason and I'm there till

00:17:29.270 --> 00:17:31.860
the Creator tells me that it's time to leave.

00:17:31.860 --> 00:17:33.890
So I wanna share with you a story.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:39.460
I was sittin in a meeting with my supervisors,
Michael Jones and, of course, Peter Fortenbaugh

00:17:39.460 --> 00:17:40.590
and he asked me one question.

00:17:40.590 --> 00:17:47.549
He said, "Why do you do what you do in the
ICC?" and my response is simple, "I love my

00:17:47.549 --> 00:17:52.909
J-O-B" You see, I teach the youth to fall
in love with technology, metaphorically, I

00:17:52.909 --> 00:17:55.780
play cupid and my arrow is imagery.

00:17:55.780 --> 00:17:57.720
Please allow me to explain.

00:17:57.720 --> 00:18:04.330
In the stages of infancy even a craftsman
chooses a topic to study and develops a disciplined

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:05.610
of mastery.

00:18:05.610 --> 00:18:10.950
You see, in truth, I lure the young people
in the ICC by bringing life to originality

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:16.789
then secretly I teach them how to increase
their vocabulary through spoken words.

00:18:16.789 --> 00:18:21.840
I curb their appetite of profanity with new
phrases and verses of opportunities.

00:18:21.840 --> 00:18:26.610
I find other ways than scrolls and lily pads
to tell stories of struggles of not having

00:18:26.610 --> 00:18:27.610
a dad.

00:18:27.610 --> 00:18:31.830
We color inside the lines with the fine tunings
of rhythm and rhymes.

00:18:31.830 --> 00:18:37.049
I am a modern day griot and I combine the
West African traditions with our initiatives

00:18:37.049 --> 00:18:38.409
and missions.

00:18:38.409 --> 00:18:44.870
That village in the Proverbs that they speak
of to raise a family is calling us to a higher

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:45.890
place of creativity.

00:18:45.890 --> 00:18:49.539
You see, this J-O-B allows me to be me.

00:18:49.539 --> 00:18:55.010
And when the Most High has given you the gift
to work with babies there's no time for complacency.

00:18:55.010 --> 00:18:58.830
You gotta bring ya "A" game to the table with
lots of energy.

00:18:58.830 --> 00:19:03.450
There's no clock to punch cause a 9 to 5 is
unheard of when paid by salary.

00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:08.980
And if the truth were told, there's no dollar
amount or silver and gold that could compensate

00:19:08.980 --> 00:19:10.370
me for my competency.

00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:14.630
I don't do this for the money and I don't
do this just to be doin' something, see, as

00:19:14.630 --> 00:19:20.750
a matter of fact, I don't have one but two
Master's degrees but humbly I share my story

00:19:20.750 --> 00:19:22.990
to explain what I do is not for everybody.

00:19:22.990 --> 00:19:29.169
At a young age my purpose was spelled out
for me combining spoken word and technology

00:19:29.169 --> 00:19:30.850
is why I'm here, see.

00:19:30.850 --> 00:19:36.299
Case and point remember now, I play cupid
and Alfi, a young man I shot with imagery,

00:19:36.299 --> 00:19:38.350
he enters my department daily.

00:19:38.350 --> 00:19:44.490
His afternoons begins with givin' me a hug
and then briefly he brings life to his truths

00:19:44.490 --> 00:19:45.490
with sincerity.

00:19:45.490 --> 00:19:52.120
I listen intently as his non verbal speak
directly and though I am exploring the possibilities

00:19:52.120 --> 00:19:57.630
of how to capture this moment with Adobe and
how not to exploit but to document his story,

00:19:57.630 --> 00:20:02.700
his words are spoken with vitality and by
the time he takes a breath and begins to breathe

00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:06.010
freely
[Takes a deep breath]

00:20:06.010 --> 00:20:11.460
&gt;&gt;Cherie Kabba: in one hand I placed a camera,
in the other a tri P-O-D.

00:20:11.460 --> 00:20:16.889
You see, Alfi now has my media crew and my
quest to continue this journey is never complete

00:20:16.889 --> 00:20:22.419
cause the reality of this J-O-B is it's not
a job but a lifestyle for myself and others

00:20:22.419 --> 00:20:28.279
like me and it is my responsibility to my
ancestors to carry the oral traditions until

00:20:28.279 --> 00:20:29.279
infinity.

00:20:29.279 --> 00:20:33.750
Now, don't get all caught up in this delivery
cause for a couple of decades I been doin'

00:20:33.750 --> 00:20:34.750
me.

00:20:34.750 --> 00:20:39.350
Don't mistake my words for hustle and flows,
aint no pimp in me, just L-O-V-E.

00:20:39.350 --> 00:20:46.799
And until technology is mandatory universally
my quest will forever be incomplete.

00:20:46.799 --> 00:20:52.440
So Pete, increasing literacy via technology
is why I do what I do in the ICC.

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:53.929
Thank you.

00:20:53.929 --> 00:20:55.419
[Applause]
[Cheering]

00:20:55.419 --> 00:20:59.149
&gt;&gt;Peter Fortenbaugh: Ms. Chillin', unbelievable.

00:20:59.149 --> 00:21:04.660
That's why I go to work every day.

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:05.660
Fantastic.

00:21:05.660 --> 00:21:09.070
Now I'd like to ask two of our fine young
gentlemen from the Redwood City Clubhouse

00:21:09.070 --> 00:21:11.970
are gonna come up and share their stories.

00:21:11.970 --> 00:21:19.429
So [Lalo Salvadra] and Diamante Horton are
two of our Peapod Academy music stars and

00:21:19.429 --> 00:21:23.600
they're gonna share their story and then after
they share their story we're gonna be treated

00:21:23.600 --> 00:21:27.409
to another song, another video and then a
live song they're gonna sing for us.

00:21:27.409 --> 00:21:29.199
Lalo, you first.

00:21:29.199 --> 00:21:32.629
&gt;&gt; [Jose Salvadra]: So, thank you Peter.

00:21:32.629 --> 00:21:35.490
My name is [Jose Salvadra].

00:21:35.490 --> 00:21:40.860
I'm 19 years old and I am currently enrolled
in Cosway Polytechnical College and I am a

00:21:40.860 --> 00:21:45.330
former member of the Boys and Girls Club of
the Peninsula, Mervin G. Morris Clubhouse

00:21:45.330 --> 00:21:46.669
to be specific.

00:21:46.669 --> 00:21:53.680
I first became involved with the club about
3 and a half years ago.

00:21:53.680 --> 00:22:01.000
I was really interested in music as a child
and also in high school and I began experimenting

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:07.340
with music at home just free downloadable
software, actually creating the music and

00:22:07.340 --> 00:22:11.919
I showed one of my projects to one of my friends
not knowing that she was a member of the Boys

00:22:11.919 --> 00:22:12.919
and Girls Club.

00:22:12.919 --> 00:22:16.350
So when she heard it she told me, she was
like, "Oh, well you should come to the Boys

00:22:16.350 --> 00:22:19.970
and Girls Club" and I was like, "Well, what's
at the Boys and Girls Club?

00:22:19.970 --> 00:22:24.750
Isn't it just like a place to take your kids
to babysit?" and she was like, "No, you know,

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:29.269
they have a music studio, they have a bunch
of other programs and it's very teen oriented

00:22:29.269 --> 00:22:30.940
unlike what most people think."

00:22:30.940 --> 00:22:35.299
And a lot of people did think that it was
like a place to babysit kids and so as soon

00:22:35.299 --> 00:22:39.890
as she mentioned the studio I was like, "Oh,
you know, I've been dying to get the experience

00:22:39.890 --> 00:22:44.679
to be in an actual professional studio, what
the environments like."

00:22:44.679 --> 00:22:50.360
So I went and as soon as I walked in everyone
was welcoming me, "Oh, hello how you doing?

00:22:50.360 --> 00:22:51.409
What's your name?

00:22:51.409 --> 00:22:52.649
Oh, I'm so and so."

00:22:52.649 --> 00:22:58.367
So I was just like, "Wow, you don't even know
me why are you talking to me?"

00:22:58.367 --> 00:23:02.080
So I spent the whole day there and I really
enjoyed my time there and I was like, "Wow,

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:05.210
these people are asking about me and they
don't even know who I am.

00:23:05.210 --> 00:23:09.419
They actually showed interest to find out
who I am, what I do."

00:23:09.419 --> 00:23:16.650
So, you know, over time I started going once,
twice a week, three times a week, four times

00:23:16.650 --> 00:23:20.629
a week, I was there all week, they had to
start kicking me out when it was closing time

00:23:20.629 --> 00:23:22.440
and I would always be in the studio.

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:25.460
Now at this time I had just lost somebody.

00:23:25.460 --> 00:23:32.450
A dear friend of mine who I grew up with and
I really didn't know how to deal with it and

00:23:32.450 --> 00:23:36.950
then this was prior to joining the Boys and
Girls Club so I was kind of lost, didn't really

00:23:36.950 --> 00:23:42.240
know where to go, my personal life suffered
dearly as well as my academics.

00:23:42.240 --> 00:23:48.059
But, being at the Boys and Girls Club really,
really, they really showed me that support

00:23:48.059 --> 00:23:54.629
because, like, I'd go in daylight in the studio
and I'd come out, like, and it was already

00:23:54.629 --> 00:23:55.629
dark.

00:23:55.629 --> 00:24:00.779
I started joining other programs such as the
Keystone program and the College Bound program.

00:24:00.779 --> 00:24:07.110
And the Boys and Girls Club found out that
I wasn't doing so hot with my academics and

00:24:07.110 --> 00:24:11.490
this is what really drew me in is that they're
very academic based so they said, "If you

00:24:11.490 --> 00:24:13.559
don't get your grades right you can't go into
the studio."

00:24:13.559 --> 00:24:17.759
So, me being me, I was like, "No, I have to
be in the studio."

00:24:17.759 --> 00:24:24.520
So that gave me an incentive, they found my
weak point and they made it my forte and I

00:24:24.520 --> 00:24:29.690
started working and I started working on my
academics, my grades increased and, you know,

00:24:29.690 --> 00:24:34.360
I was just very involved and, you know, kept
me out of trouble.

00:24:34.360 --> 00:24:40.820
A couple years passed by, graduation's coming
up and, you know, there was that support,

00:24:40.820 --> 00:24:41.820
you know, "You got this.

00:24:41.820 --> 00:24:43.249
You're gonna graduate."

00:24:43.249 --> 00:24:47.960
And with all my involvement, all the events,
just all my involvement with the Boys and

00:24:47.960 --> 00:24:53.020
Girls Club I was able to unknowingly build
a portfolio for myself.

00:24:53.020 --> 00:25:00.659
So this is what ultimately, you know, led
me to college and now what I plan to do is,

00:25:00.659 --> 00:25:07.281
within a year and a half, obtain my Bachelor's
degree and further pursue a Master's degree

00:25:07.281 --> 00:25:14.419
in music business and production and entrepreneurship
and what I wanna do is just take everything

00:25:14.419 --> 00:25:18.419
that the Boys and Girls Club did for me, through
the obstacles that I came over the past few

00:25:18.419 --> 00:25:24.019
years and I wanna be able to give back and
give back the same feeling, the same positivity,

00:25:24.019 --> 00:25:27.799
the same difference in the community that
they gave to me, to somebody else, for the

00:25:27.799 --> 00:25:30.669
next generation.

00:25:30.669 --> 00:25:33.360
[Applause]

00:25:33.360 --> 00:25:41.450
&gt;&gt;Diamante Horton: Hello.

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:43.530
I'm Diamante Horton.

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:49.462
I was born in Portland, Oregon and then I
had moved down to Washington and then down

00:25:49.462 --> 00:25:56.860
to California, Redwood City and then I moved
to Patterson but between all that I kept a

00:25:56.860 --> 00:26:02.960
real strong bond with the Redwood City Boys
and Girls Club.

00:26:02.960 --> 00:26:09.509
I was raised in a low income family.

00:26:09.509 --> 00:26:14.980
I was living in like an apartment, like one
bedroom.

00:26:14.980 --> 00:26:20.549
My mother slept on the floor and she gave
me the mattress.

00:26:20.549 --> 00:26:28.610
I was like so broke, so young that I didn't
notice what rich or what wealthy or a middle

00:26:28.610 --> 00:26:33.039
class family looked like I just thought I
was, I just thought I had it all.

00:26:33.039 --> 00:26:37.970
I was real happy with just nothing.

00:26:37.970 --> 00:26:45.029
Let me see, when I was in third grade my mother
had, she didn't want me out on the streets

00:26:45.029 --> 00:26:49.780
so she had signed me up for the Boys and Girls
Club but out of rebellion I would just, like,

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:56.409
leave, I would just skip Boys and Girls Club.

00:26:56.409 --> 00:27:04.370
I did that all the way to middle school and
I'm a real shy person but ironically I was

00:27:04.370 --> 00:27:11.289
with an outgoing crowd that was really up
to no good.

00:27:11.289 --> 00:27:21.139
I've been like firsthand witness to drug abuse
and just a lot of violence, gang violence,

00:27:21.139 --> 00:27:29.409
gang affiliation, shootings; break ins, just
like it's a real twisted life.

00:27:29.409 --> 00:27:36.169
Like your own sister's, like, a sex slave
and it's just crazy.

00:27:36.169 --> 00:27:43.789
Like, you're not, you're not, I don't know,
you're just not a kid.

00:27:43.789 --> 00:27:47.970
Like everyone would look at you and be like,
"Oh, there's this kid" like things happen

00:27:47.970 --> 00:27:49.980
in your mind.

00:27:49.980 --> 00:27:55.880
Like, it just changes your perspective of
life so I didn't really feel like I had a

00:27:55.880 --> 00:27:58.940
path to go anywhere.

00:27:58.940 --> 00:28:06.120
So one day, since I wouldn't, I was shy so
I wouldn't speak a lot I would just start

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:07.120
writing.

00:28:07.120 --> 00:28:14.320
I wrote lyrics because I didn't know how to,
I didn't know how to ask for help, I didn't

00:28:14.320 --> 00:28:19.149
know, I didn't know if I should say anything
so I just wrote lyrics and that was my outlet,

00:28:19.149 --> 00:28:21.820
I felt better.

00:28:21.820 --> 00:28:26.389
Pretty soon, like, in a matter of minutes
it became an obsession, it was like my drug,

00:28:26.389 --> 00:28:27.730
I needed to write lyrics.

00:28:27.730 --> 00:28:34.059
I used to fill notebooks up, front and back
just one page a night or something, maybe

00:28:34.059 --> 00:28:36.919
two.

00:28:36.919 --> 00:28:42.529
And then my, I went back, my mother had signed
up my siblings for the Boys and Girls Club,

00:28:42.529 --> 00:28:47.269
so I went back, one day I went to go pick
up my sister and I had seen they had a music

00:28:47.269 --> 00:28:50.860
studio and I was like, "Oh man.

00:28:50.860 --> 00:28:52.909
I need to look at that."

00:28:52.909 --> 00:28:57.230
So I signed up, I went back to the Boys and
Girls Club as a member.

00:28:57.230 --> 00:29:02.529
I got into the music.

00:29:02.529 --> 00:29:11.639
My grades were really low and they were like,
"You need to have at least a 2.5 to be able

00:29:11.639 --> 00:29:16.369
to use the music equipment" and, you know,
my grades just shot up.

00:29:16.369 --> 00:29:24.230
Like, I was, like all throughout my academic
years my teachers would say, "You know, your

00:29:24.230 --> 00:29:26.029
son might have to repeat my grade."

00:29:26.029 --> 00:29:30.210
Like every year the teacher would tell my
mom that your son might have to repeat my

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:32.690
class and my mom was just so worried.

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:38.419
So that was cool how they were like, "Yeah,
you gotta do well" and they had tutors, they

00:29:38.419 --> 00:29:41.710
had, they had everything you need.

00:29:41.710 --> 00:29:44.059
So they really helped me.

00:29:44.059 --> 00:29:53.240
I went from that shy kid with that street
life to; I traded all that in for the knowledge

00:29:53.240 --> 00:29:57.970
of music and to pave a better road to positivity.

00:29:57.970 --> 00:30:07.289
So now I'm attending Cogswell Polytechnical
College in Sunnyvale, double majoring in audio

00:30:07.289 --> 00:30:18.019
engineering and entrepreneurship and I just
wanna say that even, not even your friends

00:30:18.019 --> 00:30:27.590
can try to persuade, what do I wanna say,
not even people around you could be a negative

00:30:27.590 --> 00:30:32.450
influence, you know, you have to take it upon
yourself to choose the right path.

00:30:32.450 --> 00:30:35.289
Thank you.

